Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa says state capture in any form is &#8220;abhorrent&#8221; and should not be tolerated by South Africans. PARLIAMENT - Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa says that President Jacob Zuma is consulting his lawyers about setting up a commission of inquiry into allegations of state capture.Ramaphosa was answering questions from MPs in Parliament on Wednesday.He was asked by African National Congress (ANC) MP Mondli Gungubele about steps government was taking to restore public confidence in state-owned entities.Ramaphosa says that an independent commission of inquiry must take place as a matter of urgency. Various allegations have been made in the public domain and much evidence has also been published about undue influence of some people who it has been found may well have had undue influence. Rampahosa says state capture in any form is abhorrent and should not be tolerated by South Africans. It is in the interest of all South Africans that such a commission is established as quickly as possible so that all those with evidence can present it to a competent body and those implicated have an opportunity to respond to the allegations against them. Rampahosa says President Zuma is meeting with his lawyer to find ways of establishing an inquiry.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)